    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="534"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d534">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Moscow Embassy Files—897.6 Berlin Route</note>
                <head>No. 534<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Soviet Assistant Foreign Commissar</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_VAY1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Vyshinsky</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_HK1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-11">July 11,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: Acknowledging receipt of your
                    letter of July 7<note n="1" xml:id="d534fn1">Not printed.</note> concerning the
                    establishment in Berlin of a civil airlines connection served by American and
                    Soviet airplanes, I must remind you that in our conversation of June 15 [<hi
                        rend="italic">sic</hi>] I called your attention to the fact that practically
                    speaking there has already been considerable improvement in air communications
                    over the given route and that I recognize the importance of this matter, but I
                    do not believe that at the present time this question is sufficiently prepared
                    for discussion in substance. As to the future, I can inform you only upon
                    receipt of instructions from the Soviet Government.</p>
                <p>Please accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>A. <persName corresp="#p_V2">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vyshinski</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
